    value: 밭에 곡식을 심으면 몇 배의 수확을 얻을 수 있는 것처럼 부처를 공양하면 복을 받는다는 설.
english:
  title: Record of the Great Sutra Repository Hall at Shinnyul-sa Temple in Yeohung County
  author: Lee Sung-in
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Minister of the Three Departments, the Venerable Master Mok-eun of Hansan, commanded me to record these words:

    "In the seventh month of the year Gyeongseul of the Great Virtue era, on the third day, my grandfather, the Lord of Jeongeup, passed away from illness. My father, the Venerable Master Gajeon of Munhyo, was but thirteen years old, yet performed the funeral rites with perfect propriety. In the tenth month of the year Gyeongin of the Zhizheng era, on the twentieth day, my grandmother passed away from illness. My father conducted all ceremonies according to ritual. He invited monks and had Buddhist sutras recited at the temple in our village. My father often lamented, saying, 'Where now shall I place my reliance? Upon what shall I depend?' Then the Venerable Chong-gong of Naman addressed my father thus: 'If you truly wish to employ our Buddhist teaching to obtain blessings for your parents in the afterlife, why not undertake to print one complete collection of the Buddhist canon? All our teachings dwell herein.' My father immediately made a vow before the Buddha image.

    The following year, on the first day of the first month of Sinmyo, my father unfortunately passed away while still in mourning clothes. I hastened back from the north to observe the funeral rites and requested the Venerable Chong-gong to recite sutras. I spoke of my father's vow, yet being consumed by grief, I could not attend to such matters. After my mourning ended, I was fortunate to pass the civil examination and received an official position. Fearing I might neglect my duties, I could not spare thought for my father's unfulfilled wish. The Venerable Chong-gong sent me many letters, saying, 'How can you abandon your father's vow?' Yet I merely wrote back in sorrow, offering no resolution.

    In the ninth month of the year Sinhae of the Hongwu era, on the twenty-sixth day, my mother, the Lady Kim, also passed away from illness. Scarcely had my mourning period ended when I fell gravely ill. On the twenty-third day of the ninth month of the year GapIn, our sovereign passed into the realm beyond. I reflected deeply that my father had served our sovereign faithfully since his early princely days for many years, and I myself received my post through his grace. Though our family received boundless favor, we had never offered even the slightest return. Now that our sovereign had departed, what pain could be deeper?

    In the year Gimmi, the Venerable Chong-gong descended from the mountains and spoke to me thus: 'Now I have reached seventy-four years of age. By fortune I have not perished, and behold, we meet again. Is this mere chance? Your father's words remain clear in my ears. Do you remember still?' My heart ached deeply, and I replied, 'Is there not in this very work a way to seek blessings for our sovereign above, and to fulfill my father's intentions below? Is there not?'

    When I recovered from my illness, I had just completed writing the stupa inscription for the Venerable Raon. Yet when I considered my own strength, I found it insufficient. The only ones capable of fulfilling my father's wish were the Venerable Raon's disciples. I sent word immediately, and two monks called무급 and Subok came forth with their assembly and offered their support.

    From the second month of the year Gyeongsin, they gathered alms according to circumstance. Gak-cham gathered in Sunheung, Gak-jam in Andong, Gak-hong in Yeonghai, Do-hye in Cheongju, Gak-yeon in Chungju, Gak-un in Pyeongyang, Beom-ung in Bongju, and Ji-bo in Aju, encouraging the faithful to give generously. Paper transformed from bark, and ink refined from stone. In the fourth month of the year Sinyou, they printed the sutras, vinaya, and commentaries. In the ninth month, they bound the volumes. In the tenth month, the Venerable Gak-ju inscribed titles in gold, and Gak-bong prepared the binding cloth. In the twelfth month, Seong-gong crafted the storage boxes. From morning to night, the elderly woman Myo-an of Gukshin Village never tired of feeding the monks with rice, her devotion unwavering. In the first month of the year Imsul, they completed a final examination at Yeongthong-sa Temple. In the fourth month, the volumes were placed on boats and transported to Shinnyul-sa in Yeohung County—the very place where the Venerable Raon attained nirvana.

    The Lord of Hwashan took charge of the title inscriptions and, together with the faithful patrons, provided resources. The Venerable Soon of Dong-am oversaw all construction. They built a two-story repository hall on the southern side of the temple, decorating it with brilliant paintings. Upon completion, they enshrined the printed sutras within. Sutra recitation ceremonies are held in the fifth month, the ninth month, and now in the first month of this year Gyehae—three times yearly according to established custom.

    Within the hall stands an image of Vairocana Buddha, life-sized, at its center. The Lord of Tangseong erected an image of Samantabhadra Bodhisattva in honor of his deceased daughter. The Lady Kang provided an image of Manjushri Bodhisattva through her charitable works. Thus the assembly of all beings may approach with reverence and devotion.

    Alas! More than thirty years have passed, yet now my father's vow is finally realized. How can I not rejoice? And indeed, through this great merit, we invoke blessings for our sovereign's longevity and the nation's prosperity without end.

    The monks wish to erect a stone tablet to instruct future generations. They have asked me to compose these words:

    The way of Buddha is pure and sublime, untouched by even a speck of dust, transcendent above all creation. The wise and virtuous have always found joy in this teaching. Yet the teachings also speak of what is called the field of merit and the benefit of virtue. Thus loyal ministers and filial sons, seeking to repay the profound grace of sovereign and parent, employ every means to this end, and thus necessarily take refuge in this path. It is fitting that Buddhist scriptures spread widely in the world. The Venerable Master Gajeon first initiated this work, the Venerable Master Mok-eun carried it forward, and at last this treasury of dharma was realized, bringing merit to sovereign and parent. Is this not the supreme devotion of loyal ministers and filial sons? Alas, who among us is not a subject and child? From this day unto ten thousand ages hence, all who feel the stirring of reverence toward that which is heavenly will surely find it here—of this I have no doubt. How could I not gladly inscribe these words? As for those of the four assemblies who donated their wealth and labor to aid this work, their names are inscribed upon the back of this stone."

    So spoke Lee Sung-in, who dared not refuse this solemn charge.
  footnotes:
    - 'The ''field of merit'' (福田利益) is a Buddhist metaphor: just as planting seeds in a field yields abundant harvest, so does venerating the Buddha bring forth spiritual benefit and blessing.'
    - 'The ''four assemblies'' (四衆) refer to Buddhist sangha members and laypeople: monks, nuns, laymen, and laywomen.'
    - Shinnyul-sa Temple remains a significant historical site in Korea, and this sutra repository represents an important instance of printed Buddhist canon from the early Joseon period.
